Without doubt the best wipeout clone on Android, but lack of thrust control makes it feel like an on rails racer - the thrill of slowing down and braking before a hairpin turn and accelerating out is lost, and it's too late to add this now as the tracks are designed for flat out racing, if games like need for speed and riptide can manage to have manual throttle control there is no excuse. Also the turning physics are very basic - don't expect aerodynamic slides around corners.  That said the visuals are superb and it offers some unique gameplay modes.

This is an extremely polished racer with no obvious flaws. PROTIP: Start with Phase 1 to master the basic mechanics of the game (steering, polarity, boosts, track layout, etc.); then move on to Phase 2 when you've got Phase 1 down. After mastering Phases 1 and 2, you'll be skilled enough to compete in Phase 3. Resist the urge to jump straight to Phase 3, because Phases 1 and 2 lay the foundation for Phase 3. (Nexus 5)

It's obvious that this is a good looking game, and it mimics the Wipeout style nicely. But its fatal flaw is the controls. They're responsive enough, but they make the same mistake as Flashout 3D: there's a degree of auto-steering. That is, the game will automatically steer you through small turns, and auto-center you on the track. I get the idea, steering on a phone is hard, but that makes it extremely difficult to tell what exactly a turn will do.Behavior isnt predictable, and that kills a racing game.

I know a lot of people are gripping about the microtransactions, but i actually don't mind it and i think the prices are pretty fair. I mean they have to make money somehow.   What i would like to see: A track designer of some sort, allowing you to drop down track and decorate the scenario, including where the polarity fields are and everything else. The game is good, great graphics and sound. But the gameplay is a let-down for me, I tried it with a PS3 Bluetooth controller when I first read Pixelbite's update description mentioning "Improved key-mapping for controller support". I can confirm, it has NOT been improved, unless you use an XBox controller to play it. Using a PS3 controller, the only thing that works with the game is the left stick, nothing else. No boosting button, no fire button, nothing. So I tried it with touch controls, I thought that it could be more enjoyable that way. Man, was I wrong. It gets to be even worse. Too much precision required to play it using touch controls. One other BIG issue is the "HD" graphics. When I was playing it with my controller, I noticed frame drops and my controller's commands reception delay from the game. So please add PS3 Bluetooth controller Profile (and PS3 button icons) and optimize the HD graphics for the Tegra 2-based Transformer TF101 and I'll give this game a 5* review.

This game could be great. First, the default sensitivities are way too high. I can see most people quitting the game after one race because it's uncontrollable until manually adjusted. Second, the enemy Ai is  ridiculously out of hand. I've gotten very good at  handling and boosting, to the point where I regularly get perfect laps, yet I will still finish in last place no where even near the other racers. I've seen them fly by me while I'm at full boost. It's either a bug, overtuned rubberbanding, or worse.

Great! Graphics are awesome, the music is pretty decent, and the energy system is a nice breath of fresh air. Why only 4 stars? Controls can either be tweaked to be either too responsive or not responsive enough. Perhaps remedy this with native gamepad support? I'd kill to hook this up to my TV and play that way. Also, there needs to be a better indicator for polarity changes. Whilst playing, I look straight off into the distance to know what's coming up, only ever occasionally looking at the area surrounding the vehicle. I know the edges of the screen change tint, the colour on the ship changes too, and a small text box comes up with a coloured notification. However, none of these do a great job indicating the polarity change - especially in the heat of the moment. I suggest maybe an almighty glow surrounding your vehicle? Not only would it look great, but it would also stand out more. I would not need to take my eyes off the race if I could see out of the corner of my eyes that my vehicles' glow changed from an intense red to a stunning emerald green. Or even have the track lines change colour. Great game, but address these issues, and it's a definite 5 stars and classic status!
